{"id":"0811.1985","submitter":"Eugene Chiang","authors":"E. Chiang (UCB), E. Kite (UCB), P. Kalas (UCB), J. R. Graham (UCB),\n  and M. Clampin (NASA Goddard Space Flight Center)","title":"Fomalhaut's Debris Disk and Planet: Constraining the Mass of Fomalhaut b\n  From Disk Morphology","comments":"Final version. If Fomalhaut b's orbit is apsidally aligned with the\n  belt's, then the planet mass is 0.5 Jupiter masses. The procedure to estimate\n  Fom b's deprojected distance from the star is better explained","journal-ref":"Astrophys.J.693:734-749,2009","doi":"10.1088/0004-637X/693/1/734","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Following the optical imaging of the exoplanet candidate Fomalhaut b (Fom b),\nwe present a numerical model of how Fomalhaut's debris disk is gravitationally\nshaped by an interior planet. The model is simple, adaptable to other debris\ndisks, and can be extended to accommodate multiple planets. If Fom b is the\ndominant perturber of the belt, then to produce the observed disk morphology it\nmust have a mass < 3 Jupiter masses. If the belt and planet orbits are\napsidally aligned, our model predicts a planet mass of 0.5 Jupiter masses. The\ninner edge of the debris disk at 133 AU lies at the periphery of Fom b's\nchaotic zone, and the mean disk eccentricity of 0.11 is secularly forced by the\nplanet, supporting predictions made prior to the discovery of Fom b. However,\nprevious mass constraints based on disk morphology rely on several\noversimplifications. We explain why our constraint is more reliable. It is\nbased on a global model of the disk that is not restricted to the planet's\nchaotic zone boundary. Moreover, we screen disk parent bodies for dynamical\nstability over the system age of 100 Myr, and model them separately from their\ndust grain progeny; the latter's orbits are strongly affected by radiation\npressure and their lifetimes are limited to 0.1 Myr by destructive grain-grain\ncollisions. The single planet model predicts that planet and disk orbits be\napsidally aligned. Fom b's nominal space velocity does not bear this out, but\nthe astrometric uncertainties may be large. If the apsidal misalignment is\nreal, our upper mass limit of 3 Jupiter masses still holds. The belt contains\nat least 3 Earth masses of solids that are grinding down to dust. Such a large\nmass in solids is consistent with Fom b having formed in situ.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Nov 2008 18:23:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 19 Nov 2008 06:52:30 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 26 Feb 2009 05:08:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-02-11"}
